{"title_page": "Lansdowne portrait", "text_new": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Gilbert Stuart, George Washington (Lansdowne portrait, 1796).jpg\n| title=''George Washington''<br>(''Lansdowne portrait of George Washington'')\n| artist=Gilbert Stuart\n| caption= \n| year=1796\n| medium=Oil on canvas\n| height_metric=247.6\n| width_metric=158.7\n| height_imperial=97.5\n| width_imperial=62.5\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| museum=[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, D.C.\n| italic title=no\n}}\nThe '''Lansdowne portrait''' is an [[cultural icon|icon]]ic life-size portrait of [[George Washington]] painted by [[Gilbert Stuart]] in 1796. It depicts the 64-year-old [[President of the United States]] during his final year in office. The portrait was a gift to former [[British Prime Minister]] [[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne|William Petty, 1st Marquess of Lansdowne]], and spent more than 170 years in England.\n\nStuart painted three copies of the Lansdowne, and five portraits that were closely related to it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|175}} The most famous of the copies is in the [[East Room]] of the [[White House]]. Numerous other artists also have painted copies.\n\nTo preclude the original portrait's possible sale at auction, the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] in Washington, D.C. purchased it in 2001 for $20,000,000.<ref name=\"Kilian\">Michael Kilian, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-03-14-0103140255-story.html \"Timely Donation Saves Portrait of Washington from the Auction Block,\"] ''The Chicago Tribune'', March 14, 2001.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Lansdowne portrait likely (and fancifully) depicts President Washington's December 7, 1795 annual address to the [[4th United States Congress|Fourth U.S. Congress]].<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} The highly-unpopular [[Jay Treaty]], settling claims between the United States and Great Britain left over from the Revolutionary War, had been presented for approval to the U.S. Senate earlier in the year. The Senate held a special session to debate the treaty in June, at which opposition to it had been fierce. Only two-thirds of the 30 senators (the minimum required under the U.S. Constitution) approved the treaty in mid-August, and Washington, who strongly supported the treaty, signed it in late August.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} In his annual address to Congress, on the opening day of its next session, President Washington acknowledged the struggle over the treaty and called for unity.<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29437 George Washington - Seventh Annual Address to Congress], from The American Presidency Project.</ref> The portrait's paper, pen and inkwell may allude to his signing of the treaty.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} There was lingering resentment in the House of Representatives, which expressed its displeasure by declining to appropriate funding for the treaty's implementation until April 1796.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\">Ellen G. Miles, \"\"Gilbert Stuart's 'Lansdowne' Portrait of George Washington: From Private Diplomatic Gift to State Portrait,\" lecture given at the National Portrait Gallery, September 25, 2014.[https://vimeo.com/133491164]</ref>\n\nIn England, the Lansdowne portrait was celebrated as Washington's endorsement of the Jay Treaty:\n\n<blockquote>The portrait presented by the President {{sic}} to the Marquis of Lansdowne is one of the finest pictures we have seen since the death of Reynolds. The dress he wears is plain black velvet; he has his sword on, upon the hilt of which one hand rests while the other is extended, as the figure is standing and addressing the Hall of Assembly. The point of time is that when he recommended inviolable union between America and Great Britain.<ref>''The Oracle and Public Advertiser'' (London), May 15, 1797.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWashington's December 7, 1795 address was the last that he delivered to Congress ''in person''. The following year the President published his [[George Washington's Farewell Address|Farewell Address]] in the newspapers, rather than delivering it to Congress.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}}\n\n==Stuart==\nStuart and his family were [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalists]], and moved from Rhode Island to Canada early in the [[American Revolution|Revolutionary War]].<ref name=\"NGA 2010\">[http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2005/stuart/philadelphia.shtm National Gallery of Art] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410110519/http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2005/stuart/philadelphia.shtm |date=April 10, 2010 }}. ''Gilbert Stuart''. Philadelphia (1794\u20131803). Accessed: October 15, 2019.</ref> Stuart himself lived and painted in [[London]] from 1775 to 1787, and in [[Dublin]] from 1787 to 1793.<ref name=\"NGA 2010\"/> Following almost eighteen years abroad, the artist returned to the United States in early 1793.<ref name=\"NGA 2010\"/>\n\n[[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne|Lord Lansdowne]] &ndash; who as [[British Prime Minister]] had secured a peaceful end to the War &ndash; commissioned Stuart to paint a portrait of George Washington.<ref>[https://history.blog.gov.uk/2015/08/26/william-petty-2nd-earl-of-shelburne-whig-1782-1783/ William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne (Whig, 1782-1783)], from The National Archives (UK.gov).</ref> Lansdowne may have placed the order prior to the artist's 1793 return to the United States.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|80\u201381}} Stuart lived and worked in New York City for a year and a half before moving to Philadelphia in November 1794.<ref name=\"Zygmont\">\nBryan Zygmont, [https://www.khanacademy.org/humanities/art-americas/british-colonies/early-republic/a/gilbert-stuarts-lansdowne-portrait \"Gilbert Stuart's Lansdowne Portrait,\"] from Khan Academy.</ref> He informed his uncle in Philadelphia of his upcoming arrival: \"The object of my journey is only to secure a picture of the President, & finish yours.\"<ref>Stuart to Joseph Anthony, 2 November 1794, Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston. Quoted in Miles, pp. 129-30.</ref>\n\n[[Philadelphia]] served as the temporary national capital from 1790 to 1800 &ndash; while Washington, D.C. was under construction. Stuart was introduced to the President at one of Mrs. Washington's [[President's House (Philadelphia)|Friday evening \"drawingrooms,\"]] in December 1794.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|133}} But it was not until the following fall that Washington granted him a sitting. Meanwhile, Stuart gathered orders for portraits&mdash;among his papers is a document titled: \"A list of gentlemen who are to have copies of the portrait of the President of the United States.\" and dated: \"Philadelphia. April 20th, 1795.\"<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|87\u201388}} Lord Lansdowne's name was third on the list of thirty-two subscribers.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|87}}{{efn|In a September 25, 2014 lecture, Ellen G. Miles, Curator Emerita of the National Portrait Gallery, noted that others on Stuart's list of subscribers received copies of Washington head-and-bust portraits, but Lord Lansdowne received an original full-length portrait. She theorized that Lansdowne had ordered a standard portrait, but it was upgraded at Senator Bingham's suggestion (and expense) to an original and full-length portrait, a much more impressive gift.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/>}}\n\nAccording to [[Rembrandt Peale]], President Washington granted a single joint sitting to Stuart and him \"in the Autumn of 1795.\"<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88}} Stuart was not wholly satisfied with the resulting head-and-bust \"Vaughan-style\" portrait, but still painted between twelve and sixteen copies of it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|135}} He later claimed to have destroyed his original.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88}} \n\nWhile visiting London a decade earlier, [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[William Bingham]] of [[Pennsylvania]] and his wife, Anne Willing Bingham, had sat for a family portrait by Stuart (abandoned).<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|198}} The artist seems to have approached Mrs. Bingham for assistance in getting the President to grant him another sitting:<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|91}}\n\n{{quote|\n::Mr. Stuart, Chestnut Street.\n\n:::Sir\n\n:::&mdash; I am under promise to Mrs. Bingham to set for you to-morrow at nine o'clock, and wishing to know if it be convenient to you that should do so, whether it shall be at your own house (as she talked of the State House) I send this note to you to ask information.\n\n::::::::::::::::I am Sir, Your \n\n::::::::::::::::obedient Serv<sup>t</sup>\n\n:::::::::::::::::::Ge<sup>o</sup>. \n\n:::::::::::::::::::WASHINGTON.\n\n::Monday Evening, 11th Ap<sup>r</sup> 1796.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88\u201389}}}}\n\nAccording to Rembrandt Peale, this was the only sitting that Washington granted for the Lansdowne portrait.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\">Ellen Gross Miles, \"George Washington (The Lansdowne Portrait),\" in ''Gilbert Stuart'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2004), pp. 166-90.</ref>{{rp|168}} It took place at Stuart's studio (and lodgings) in the William Moore Smith house, at the southeast corner of 5th & Chestnut Streets.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|168}} With severely limited time, Stuart was forced to concentrate on the President's head and face.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|168}} There are multiple claims as to who posed for the body of the figure, including his landlord, Smith.{{efn|In [[George Washington Parke Custis|\"Wash\" Custis]]'s description of Washington's annual address to Congress (either 1794 or 1795, based on Thomas Jefferson's presence), he wrote: \"Washington was dressed precisely as Stuart has painted him in Lord Lansdowne's full-length portrait&mdash;\" and then proceeded to give a detailed description. On the portrait: \"The defect in the full-length is in the limbs. For the figure, a man named Smith, with whom Stuart boarded, stood&mdash;a smaller man than Washington; and the hands were painted from a wax cast of Stuart's own hand, which was much smaller than Washington's.\" On the mouth: \"Washington, at the time Stuart painted his portrait, had a set of sea-horse ivory teeth. These, just made, were too large and clumsy, and gave that peculiar appearance of the mouth seen in Stuart's picture.\"<ref>G. W. Parke Custis, ''Recollections and Private Memoirs of Washington'' (New York: Derby & Jackson, 1860), pp. 491, 520-23.</ref>}}\n\nThe portrait was begun by Stuart in his Philadelphia studio and completed in his [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] studio, the second floor of a stable some 8 miles north of the city.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|130\u201331}} The artist moved to Germantown in Summer 1796 to avoid distractions.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|165\u201366}} The Binghams had enjoyed Lord Lansdowne's hospitality in London, and persuaded Stuart to allow them to pay for the portrait.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|166, 168}} Stuart completed the Lansdowne portrait by the fall of 1796, and Senator Bingham paid his fee of $1,000.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|170}} Bingham had an ornate frame made for the portrait, and arranged for it to be shipped to England in late November. Lord Lansdowne had received the portrait by March 5, 1797, when he mentioned it in a letter.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|92}} Lansdowne's letter of thanks to Mrs. Bingham survives, but is undated:\n\n<blockquote>A very fine portrait of the greatest man living in a magnificent frame found its way into my hall, with no one thing left for me to do regarding it, except to thank the amiable donor of it. It is universally approv'd and admir'd, and I see with satisfaction, that there is no one who does not turn away from every thing else, to pay their homage to General Washington. Among many circumstances which contribute to enhance the value of it, I shall always consider the quarter from whence it comes as most flattering, & I look forward with the greatest pleasure to the time of shewing you and Mr. Bingham where I have plac'd it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|170}}</blockquote>\n\n===Copies===\nStuart's first copy of the portrait was for the Binghams (now at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]), and would have been completed before the original left his studio in late 1796.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/> The President and First Lady visited Germantown on January 7, 1797: \"Road [rode] to German Town with Mrs. Washington to see Mr. Stuarts paintings.\"<ref>Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds., ''The Diaries of George Washington, Volume 6'' (Charlottesville: University of Virginia Press, 1976&ndash;79), p. 229.</ref> The Bingham copy was still in the studio on July 27, 1797, where Robert Gilmor Jr. viewed it.<ref name=\"Gilmor\">Robert Gilmor Jr., ''Memorandums Made in a Tour to the Eastern States in the Year 1797'' (Boston: Trustees of the Boston Public Library, 1892), p. 6.</ref> The William Kerin Constable copy (now at the [[Brooklyn Museum]]) was completed that same month.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}} The Gardiner Baker copy (now at the White House) is presumed to have been the copy commissioned by [[Charles Cotesworth Pinckney]] in September 1796, likely as a diplomatic gift to France.{{efn|Art historian Ellen G. Miles has a theory as to why Charles Cotesworth Pinckney commissioned and paid for a copy of the Lansdowne portrait, but never retrieved it from Gilbert Stuart's studio.<br>[[James Monroe]] was Minister to France in 1795, when the Jay Treaty was signed. France was then at war with Great Britain, and despite his best efforts, Monroe could not convince the French government that this was a benign treaty and would not affect Franco-American relations. President Washington recalled Monroe, and nominated Pinckney as his successor. Pinckney was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in September 1796, and arrived in Paris in November.<br>The [[French Directory]] refused to accept Pinckney's credentials, and negotiations between the countries broke down when French officials demanded a substantial bribe to do so, in what became known as the [[XYZ Affair]].<br>Miles's theory is that Pinckney's copy of the Lansdowne portrait was intended as a diplomatic gift from the U.S. to France. Pinckney's deliberate humiliation and the suspension of diplomatic relations between the countries (for nearly 5 years) caused those plans (and the portrait) to be abandoned.<br>Supporting evidence for the diplomatic gift theory is that Pinckney later sought reimbursement from Secretary of State Timothy Pickering for the $500 that he had paid to Stuart for the portrait.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/>}} Pinckney paid for but never retrieved his copy of the portrait from Stuart's studio, and the artist seems to have resold it to Baker by December 1797.<ref name=\"Stretch\">Bonnie Barrett Stretch, \"The White House Washington, If Stuart Didn't Paint It, Who Did?\" ''ArtNews'', October 1, 2004.[http://www.artnews.com/2004/10/01/the-white-house-washington/]</ref>\n\n==Provenance==\n<blockquote>After the death of Lord Lansdowne, his pictures were sold by auction. The ''Washington'' was purchased by Samuel Williams, an English {{sic}} merchant, for $2,000. Williams subsequently became insolvent, and his creditors disposed of the ''Washington'' by a lottery. Forty tickets were sold, at fifty guineas each. The picture fell to Mr. J. Delaware Lewis, a nephew of Mr. William D. Lewis, of Philadelphia. But few Americans had ever seen the picture, and Mr. William D. Lewis, who was Chairman of the Committee on Art, obtained the loan of it from his nephew for the [[1876 Centennial Exposition|Centennial Exhibition]]. It was sent out with the loan collection from England, unpacked at [[Memorial Hall (Philadelphia)|Memorial Hall]], and hung up in the British section before its arrival was known to the Fine Arts Committee. An effort was subsequently made to have it transferred to the American section, but it was unsuccessful. At the close of the Exhibition, it was returned to its owner in England.<ref name=\"Mason\">George Champlin Mason, ''The Life and Works of Gilbert Stuart'' (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1894).</ref>{{rp|13}}</blockquote>\n\n===Chronology===\n*1796 &ndash; Painted by Gilbert Stuart.\n*1797 &ndash; Presented by Senator William Bingham and his wife Anne Willing Bingham as a gift to William Petty, the first Marquis of Lansdowne (died 1805). \n*1806 &ndash; Purchased in March, at the sale of the Marquis's estate by Samuel Williams, an American merchant living in England.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1827 &ndash; Purchased through lottery by John Delaware Lewis (1774&ndash;1841), an American merchant living in England.<ref name=\"Provenance\">{{cite web |title=George Washington (Lansdowne Portrait); see section ''Provenance''|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2001.13 |website=National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution |accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> \n*1841 &ndash; Inherited by [[John Delaware Lewis]] Jr. (1828&ndash;1884), son of the American and later a British Member of Parliament<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1876 &ndash; Exhibited at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia.\n*1884 &ndash; Inherited by Herman LeRoy Lewis.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1889 &ndash; Purchased by Archibald Philip Primrose, fifth Earl of Rosebery; by family descent to Lord Harry Dalmeny.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1968 &ndash; Placed on long-term loan to the National Portrait Gallery.<ref name=\"NGA\">[http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2001.13 George Washington (Lansdowne Portrait)], from National Portrait Gallery.</ref> \n*2001 &ndash; Purchased by the National Portrait Gallery, with $20 million from [[The Donald W. Reynolds Foundation]].<ref name=\"Kilian\"/> The Foundation donated an additional $10 million to renovate the National Portrait Gallery and to fund a traveling exhibition of the portrait.<ref>[http://www.dwreynolds.org/Programs/Special/Special.htm Donald W. Reynolds Foundation, ''Special Projects'']</ref>\n\n==Description and Analysis==\n[[File:Lansdowne portrait table leg.png|140px|thumb|left|The table leg may have been inspired by a wooden [[ceremonial mace]] used by the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] (the U.S. House symbol was itself inspired by the Roman ''[[fasces]]''). The House mace was a bundle of tied reeds topped with a [[bald eagle]], an American symbol.]]\n[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington (detail of book labels) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Detail of the book bindings in the White House's copy of the Lansdowne portrait. \"UNITED STATES\" is spelled as \"UNITED SATES\" to distinguish the copy.]]\nThe painting is full of symbolism, drawn from American and [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] symbols of the [[Roman Republic]]. Stuart painted Washington from life, showing him standing up, dressed in a black [[velvet]] suit with an outstretched hand held up in an [[Eloquence|oratorical]] manner. Behind Washington is a row of two [[Doric column]]s, with another row to the left. Wrapped around and between the columns are red tasseled drapes.\n\nWashington's suit is plain and simple, and the [[sword]] he holds on his left side is a dress sword and not a battle sword (symbolizing a [[Democracy|democratic]] [[form of government]], rather than a [[monarchy]] or [[military dictatorship]]). In the sky, storm clouds appear on the left while a [[rainbow]] appears on the right, signifying the [[American Revolutionary War]] giving way to the peace and prosperity of the new [[United States]] after the 1783 [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]]. The medallion at the top of the chair shows the red, white, and blue colors of the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]].\n\nOn and under the tablecloth-draped table to the left are two [[book]]s: ''Federalist''&mdash;probably a reference to the ''[[Federalist Papers]]''&mdash;and ''Journal of Congress''&mdash;the ''[[Congressional Record]]''. Another five books are under the table: the three to the right are ''General Orders'', ''American Revolution'', and ''Constitutional Bylaws''&mdash;symbolizing Washington's leadership as [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[Continental Army]] and [[President of the Continental Congress|president]] of the [[Philadelphia Convention|Constitutional Convention]].\n\nThe [[pen]] and [[paper]] on the table signify the [[rule of law]]. The table's leg is shaped like a [[fasces]], an ancient Roman symbol of [[power (sociology)|power]] and [[authority]] (''[[imperium]]''). On the far left of the table is a [[silver]] [[inkwell]], emblazed with [[Coat of Arms of George Washington|George Washington's coat of arms]] (see [[Syng inkstand]]). A white [[quill]] rests upon silver [[dog]]s, ancient symbols of [[loyalty]]. Behind these on the table is a large black [[hat]].\n\nWashington's unusually clenched [[facial expression]] comes from his famous [[Dentures|false teeth]]. [[Jean-Antoine Houdon]]'s [[marble]] [[sculpture]] of Washington shows a more natural expression. Stuart wrote: \"When I painted him [Washington], he had just had a set of false teeth inserted, which accounts for the constrained expression so noticeable about the mouth and lower part of the face ... Houdon's [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] does not suffer from this defect.\"\n\n==Alternate versions==\n===Constable-Hamilton portrait===\nStuart painted a 1797 seated portrait of Washington, based on the Lansdowne. William Kerin Constable, who commissioned the Lansdowne copy now at the Brooklyn Museum, also commissioned the seated version.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|98}} Constable presented it to [[Alexander Hamilton]] in 1797.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|98}} The portrait remained in the Hamilton family until 1896, when it was bequeathed to the [[Lenox Library (New York City)|Lenox Library]].<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/> The Lenox Library later merged with the [[New York Public Library]]. The portrait was auctioned at Sotheby's NY, 30 November 2005, lot 3, and sold for $8,136,000.<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2005/american-paintings-drawings-sculpture-including-property-from-the-new-york-public-library-astor-lenox-and-tilden-foundations-n08134/lot.3.html George Washington (Constable-Hamilton Portrait)], from Sotheby's NY.</ref> The Constable-Hamilton Portrait is now in the collection of the [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], in [[Bentonville, Arkansas]].<ref name=\"CBMAA\">[http://collection.crystalbridges.org/objects/193/george-washington-the-constablehamilton-portrait?ctx=cf2d7cdf-4879-41e8-9884-d94fb9947503&idx=2 George Washington - The Constable-Hamilton Portrait], from Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art.</ref>\n\n===Munro-Lenox portrait===\nStuart made several changes for the Munro-Lenox portrait ({{circa}}1800):<ref name=\"SIRIS\">[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=D52X1907708G8.5587&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!47905~!2&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Lenox&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington - The Munro-Lenox Portrait], from SIRIS.</ref> Washington's head is slightly turned, and his hand is on the table, rather than gesturing into the air. The President looks directly at the viewer, rather than off to the side, which makes it a more compelling image than the Lansdowne.<ref name=\"Miles\"/> The head appears to be based on Stuart's Athenaeum portrait (the image on the one-dollar bill).<ref name=\"Miles\"/> The wall behind the President is lowered, allowing for a more dramatic scene of the sun breaking through the storm clouds. After 135 years of ownership by the [[New York Public Library]], the Munro-Lenox portrait was deassessioned and offered for auction in 2005.<ref name=\"Sotheby's\">[http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/lot.5.html/2005/american-paintings-drawings-sculpture-including-property-from-the-new-york-public-library-astor-lenox-and-tilden-foundations-n08134 George Washington - The Munro-Lenox Portrait], from Sotheby's New York.</ref> It failed to sell at auction, and was sold in a private sale for an undisclosed amount.<ref>Carol Vogel, [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/05/arts/design/05voge.html \"A Pair of New Owners for an Old President,\"] ''The New York Times'', January 5, 2007.</ref>\n\nStuart painted three full-size copies of the Munro-Lenox Portrait, one for the Connecticut State House in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]]; and two for Rhode Island&mdash;one for the State House in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], and the other for [[Old Colony House]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]].<ref name=\"Miles\">Ellen Gross Miles, \"George Washington (The Munro-Lenox Portrait),\" in ''Gilbert Stuart'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2004), pp. 186-90.</ref>\n\n==Painted by Gilbert Stuart==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\" | Type\n! width=\"18%\" | Collection\n! width=\"8%\" | Image\n! width=\"10%\" | Artist\n! width=\"9%\" | Completed\n! width=\"8%\" | Medium\n! width=\"10%\" | Dimensions\n! width=\"32%\" | Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Lansdowne type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Lansdowne portrait<ref name=\"NGA\"/><br>National Portrait Gallery,<br>Washington, D.C.\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart, George Washington (Lansdowne portrait, 1796).jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|Fall 1796\n|oil on canvas\n|247.6&nbsp;cm x 158.7&nbsp;cm<br>(97 1/2 x 62 1/2 in)\n|Begun April 12, 1796<br>Unsigned & undated\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]],<ref>[http://artandhistory.house.gov/highlights.aspx?action=view&intID=351 Office of the Clerk, U.S. House of Representatives, ''Artist Gilbert Stuart\u2019s portraits of George Washington''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915082823/http://artandhistory.house.gov/highlights.aspx?action=view&intID=351 |date=2012-09-15 }} Accessed: May 11, 2012.</ref><br>Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|[[File:Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts - Washington Foyer.jpg|100px]]<br><small>at far left</small>\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by November 1796\n|oil on canvas\n|243.8&nbsp;cm x 152.4&nbsp;cm<br>(96 in x 60 in)\n|Commissioned by Senator William Bingham.<br>First copy painted by Stuart.<br>Signed & dated: \"G. Stuart, 1796\"<ref>Helen W. Henderson, ''The Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts and Other Collections in Philadelphia'' (Boston: L. C. Page & Company, 1899), frontispiece, p. 81.[https://archive.org/stream/pennsylvaniaacad00hend_0#page/80/mode/2up]</ref> <br>Present in Stuart's [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] studio, July 1797<ref name=\"Gilmor\"/><br>1811 bequest to PAFA<ref>[https://www.pafa.org/collection/george-washington-lansdowne-portrait George Washington (Bingham portrait)], from Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts.</ref>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Brooklyn Museum]],<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\" /><br>Brooklyn, [[New York City]]\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington - Google Art Project (6966745)FXD.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|July 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|244.5&nbsp;cm x 153&nbsp;cm<br>(96 1/4 in x 60 1/4 in)\n|Commissioned by William Kerin Constable.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15VY14267968R.5068&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!41116~!2&ri=3&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Lansdowne&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=3 George Washington (Constable portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><br>Unsigned & undated<br>Constable paid Stuart $500 for \"one [portrait] of the late President of the United States at full length.\" Constable's receipt from Stuart is signed and dated \"Philadelphia. 13 July 1797.\"<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}}<br>1945 museum purchase<ref>[https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/934 George Washington, Gilbert Stuart], from Brooklyn Museum.</ref>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[White House]], [[East Room]],<br>Washington, D.C.\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington - Google Art Project.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart (and<br>William Winstanley?){{efn|The comparably poor quality of the Lansdowne copy at the White House has led to questions and conspiracy theories about its authorship.<ref name=\"Stretch\"/><br>After Stuart toured the White House with Dr. [[William Thornton]] in 1802, [[Anna Thornton|Thornton's wife]] wrote to Dolley Madison: \"He [Stuart] denies most pointedly having painted the picture in the President's house, and says he told Genl: Lee that he did not paint it&mdash;but that he bargained for it.\"<ref>Anna Maria Thornton to Dolley Madison, August 24, 1802, in David B. Mattern and Holly C. Shulman, eds. ''The Selected Letters of Dolley Payne Madison'' (Charlottesville: University of Virginia Press, 2003, pp. 50-51.</ref><br>Artist William Dunlap wrote (in 1834) that William Winstanley was hired to pack the Washington portrait bought for the White House in July 1800, and substituted his own copy for Stuart's prior to its being shipped from New York City to Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Dunlap\"/> Dunlap also reported that Winstanley had approached Stuart about putting finishing touches on his pirated Lansdowne copies, proposing that they could share the proceeds, but Stuart angrily rejected the idea.<ref name=\"Dunlap\"/><br>Regarding Stuart's denial of the White House Lansdowne, Ellen G. Miles writes: \"The comment does suggest that Stuart did not paint the entire portrait.\" ''Gilbert Stuart'' (2004), p. 181, n. 23.}}\n|by December 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|241.3&nbsp;cm x 151.9&nbsp;cm<br>(95 in x 59 3/4 in)\n|Probably commissioned by Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, September 1796, as a diplomatic gift to France.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/><br>Unsigned & undated<br>Purchased from Stuart by Gardiner Baker for $500, by December 1797.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181}}<br>Exhibited at Tammany Society Museum, New York City, February 1798.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181}}<br>Purchased for the White House for $800, July 1800.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|88}}<br>Rescued by First Lady [[Dolley Madison]] prior to the August 24, 1814 [[Burning of Washington#White House|burning of the White House]] by the British.<ref>{{cite web|title=The East Room|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/white-house-tour/the-east-room|website=The White House Historical Association|publisher=The White House Historical Association|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Constable-Hamilton type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Constable-Hamilton Portrait<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/><br>Ex collection: Lenox Library<br>Ex collection:New York Public Library<br>[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]],<br>Bentonville, Arkansas\n|[[File:Stuart-george-washington-constable-1797.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|July 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|127&nbsp;cm x 101.6&nbsp;cm<br>(50 in x 40 in)\n|Commissioned by William Kerin Constable, as a gift to Alexander Hamilton.<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/><br>Constable paid $250 for the \"half-length\" portrait. His receipt from Stuart is signed and dated \"Philadelphia. 13 July 1797.\"<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}}<br>1896 bequest to the Lenox Library (later merged with New York Public Library)<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Munro-Lenox type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Munro-Lenox Portrait<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Ex collection: Lenox Library<br>Ex collection: New York Public Library<br>Private collection\n|[[File:Munro-Lenox Portrait from NYPL.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|{{circa}}1800\n|oil on canvas\n|241.3&nbsp;cm x 162.6&nbsp;cm<br>(95 in x 64 in)\n|Commissioned by Peter Jay Munro<br>Signed \"G. St.\" (on table leg), undated<br>Donated to the Lenox Library, 1870.<br>Auctioned at Sotheby's NY, 30 November 2005, Lot 5.<ref name=\"Sotheby's\"/>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Old State House (Connecticut)|Old State House]],<br>Connecticut State Library Museum,<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=Q5251706WV553.5346&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!35638~!9&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Hartford&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Hartford portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><br>[[Hartford, Connecticut]]\n|\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|April 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|240.4&nbsp;cm x 146.1&nbsp;cm<br>(94 5/8 in x 57 1/2 in)\n|Commissioned by the [[Connecticut General Assembly]], May 1800.<ref name=\"Johnston\">Elizabeth Bryant Johnston, ''Original Portraits of Washington'' (Boston: James R. Osgood & Company, 1882).</ref>{{rp|90}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gosselin|first1=Kenneth|title=Old State House To Reopen Monday|url=http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-old-state-house-reopens-20161122-story.html|website=Hartford Courant|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tourist in My Own State: Connecticut's Old State House|url=http://www.thefrontdoorproject.com/2015/09/historic-doors/tourist-in-my-own-state-connecticuts-old-state-house/|website=The Front Door Project|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=21 September 2015}}</ref><br>Connecticut paid $600 for the portrait. The receipt, signed by Stuart and dated 4 April 1801, is in the Connecticut State Archives.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|189\u201390}}\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Rhode Island State House]],<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15DN1Q0244473.5338&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!60262~!16&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Rhode+Island&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=stuart,+gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Providence portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Rhode Island State House: A Guided Tour|url=http://sos.ri.gov/assets/downloads/documents/self-guided-state-house-tour-brochure.pdf|website=State of Rhode Island|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><br>State Reception Room, <br>[[Providence, Rhode Island]].\n|[[File:State_Reception_Room,_Rhode_Island_State_House.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by October 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|<br>(96 in x 60 in)\n|Rhode Island had statehouses in both Providence and Newport (until 1901). The [[Rhode Island General Assembly]] commissioned 2 copies of the Munro-Lenox portrait in 1800, one for each statehouse.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|89}}<br>The elaborate wooden frame was carved and gilded by Martin Jugiez, a Philadelphia carver.<ref name=\"Miles\"/><br>Both portraits (and their ornate frames) were transported by ship from Philadelphia, and arrived at Newport in October 1801.{{efn|\"The commission was at once given to Gilbert Stuart, who took pride and pleasure in painting the portraits; for which work he received $1,200. The pictures were painted in Philadelphia, where the frames were also procured at a cost of $200 each. When finished, the portraits and frames were placed in the care of Joseph Anthony & Co., of Philadelphia, by whom they were shipped to Rhode Island on board of Gibbs & Channing's sloop ''Eagle''. The pictures were received here in October 1801.\"<ref>George Champlin Mason, ''Reminiscences of Newport'' (Newport, RI: Charles E. Hammett, Jr., 1884), pp. 290-91.</ref>}}\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Old Colony House]] (formerly<br>Rhode Island State House, Newport),<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=152K1Q9C92979.5706&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!60274~!5&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=colony+house&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Newport portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><ref>James L. Yarnell, \"The Full-Length Portrait of George Washington in the Newport Colony House,\" ''Newport History: Journal of the Newport Historical Society'', nos. 72-73 (Fall 2003&ndash;Spring 2004), pp. 150-59.</ref><br>[[Newport, Rhode Island]]\n|\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by October 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|\n|Old Colony House served as a Rhode Island State House until 1901.<ref>[http://newporthistory.org/properties/colony-house/ Colony House], from Newport Historical Society.</ref><br>The elaborate wooden frame was carved and gilded by Martin Jugiez, a Philadelphia carver.<ref name=\"Miles\"/><br>Arrived by ship at Newport, October 1801.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|188}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Copies painted by other artists==\nThe Lansdowne and Munro-Lenox portraits were copied many times, and reproduced in widely circulated prints.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\">{{cite web|title=American Art: Luce Center for American Art, 5th Floor|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/american_art|website=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=25 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120101614/https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/american_art/|archivedate=29 June 2016}}</ref> William Winstanley (1775&ndash;1806), a British painter who had sold landscapes to President Washington,<ref>George Washington to the Commissioners for the District of Columbia, 5 September 1793, note 1, from National Archives.[https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/05-14-02-0019]</ref> reportedly painted six full-size copies of the Lansdowne.<ref name=\"Dunlap\">William Dunlap, ''History of the Rise and Progress of the Arts of Design in the United States'' vol. 1 (New York: George C. Scott and Co., 1834), pp. 200-02.</ref> During the 19th century, [[Jane Stuart]] (the artist's daughter) painted multiple copies of the Lansdowne in full and reduced sizes. [[Alonzo Chappel]] included elements of the Lansdowne in his {{circa}}1860 seated portrait of Washington ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]).<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/10436?sortBy=Relevance&amp;ft=Chappel%2c+Alonzo&amp;offset=0&amp;rpp=20&amp;pos=1 George Washington - Design for an Engraving, (c. 1860) by Alonzo Chappel], from Metropolitan Museum of Art.</ref>\n\n===Lansdowne type===\n* [[Catholic University]], Washington, D.C., unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181\u201382}}\n* [[Washington and Lee University]], Lexington, Virginia, unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|182}}\n* Private collection (deassessioned from the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]), unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181\u201382}}\n* [[New York State Capitol]], Albany, New York, by [[Ezra Ames]], 1813<ref>{{cite book|author1=John Caldwell, Oswaldo Rodriguez Roque, Dale T. Johnson|title=American Paintings in The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Vol. 1|date=1994|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|page=239|accessdate=31 March 2018|quote=clearly based on the Stuart Lansdowne portrait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYdWBwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA240&ots=qgszBj4zHp&dq=landsdowne%20portrait%20in%20albany%20new%20york%20capitol&pg=PA240#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n* Rayburn Room, [[U.S. Capitol]], unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), by 1816<ref>{{cite web|title=Art and Artifacts George Washington's Journey to the Rayburn Room|url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/Capitol/Rayburn-Reception-Room/Art-and-Artifacts/|website=History, Art, & Archives|publisher=US House of Representatives|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n**Inscription: \"Presented to the Legation of the United States at Madrid by [[Richard Worsam Meade I|Richard W. Meade]] of Philadelphia, December 11th, 1818.\"\n**Relocated from the U.S. Embassy in Madrid to the U.S. Capitol, 1951.\n* [[North Carolina State House]], Raleigh, North Carolina, by [[Thomas Sully]], commissioned 1816, installed 1818. Now in the House of Representatives Chamber, [[North Carolina State Capitol]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Exhibit and Reinstallation of Washington Portrait This April |url=https://www.ncdcr.gov/state-capitol-debuts-george-washington-exhibit-and-reinstallation-washington-portrait-april |publisher=[[North Carolina Department of Natural and Cultural Resources]] |date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Maryland Historical Society]], Baltimore, Maryland, unknown artist, {{circa}}1830s<ref>{{cite web|title=George Washington|url=https://www.mdhs.org/digitalimage/george-washington|website=Maryland Historical Society|publisher=Maryland Historical Society|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Providence Athenaeum]], Providence, Rhode Island, unknown Italian artist, {{circa}}1830s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Art Collection: Painting|url=https://providenceathenaeum.org/collections/art-collection/painting/|website=The Providence Athenaeum|accessdate=25 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822015129/https://providenceathenaeum.org/collections/art-collection/painting/|archivedate=22 August 2016|quote=George Washington, circa 1830s. Anonymous, after Gilbert Stuart (1755-1828). Oil on canvas. Gift of The Honorable Samuel Larned, 1838.}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Art Gallery]], Washington, D.C., by Jane Stuart, 1854.<ref>''A Catalogue of the Collection of American Paintings in The Corcoran Gallery of Art, Volume 1'' (The Corcoran Gallery of Art, 1966), p. 81.</ref>\n*[[The Greenbrier]], White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia, by Jane Stuart, mid-19th century.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=S52545711L85V.2091&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!149308~!14&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Greenbriar&index=.OW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Greenbrier)], from SIRIS.</ref>\n*Kuhl-Harrison reduced-size portrait, (36 1/4 in x 24 in), unlocated, Gilbert Stuart and Jane Stuart, 19th century.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/europeanamerican00amer_0#page/n47/mode/2up George Washington: Lansdowne Type (The Kuhl-Harrison Portrait)], from Anderson Galleries Inc., New York, 1936.</ref>\n*Reduced-size portrait, [[Redwood Library and Athenaeum]], Newport, Rhode Island, Jane Stuart, mid-19th century.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1525A46322NE1.4870&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!59811~!85&ri=23&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Stuart,+Jane&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=23 George Washington (Redwood Library)], from SIRIS.</ref>\n*[[Birmingham Museum of Art]], Birmingham, Alabama, by [[Theo Ramos|Theodore Ramos]] (1928-2018), 1965.<ref>[https://artsbma.org/collection/copy-of-lansdowne-portrait-of-george-washington-by-gilbert-stuart/ Copy of Lansdowne Portrait], from Birmingham Museum of Art.</ref> On loan to [[Alabama National Cemetery#American Village|American Village]], Montevallo, Alabama.\n<gallery>\nFile:Lansdowne portrait copy in New York State Capitol.jpg|New York State Capitol, Ezra Ames, 1813\nFile:Lansdowne copy Rayburn Room U.S. House of Representatives.jpg|Rayburn Room, U.S. Capitol, unknown artist, by 1816\nFile:House of Representatives Chamber - North Carolina State Capitol - DSC05940.JPG|North Carolina State Capitol, Thomas Sully, 1818\nFile:Lansdowne portrait of George Washington copy at Providence Athenaeum.jpg|Providence Athenaeum, unknown artist, 1830s\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cervin Robinson, Photographer, July 15, 1970 VIEW OF INTERIOR FROM READING (CENTER) ROOM TO DOOR WEST. - Redwood Library, 50 Bellevue Avenue, HABS RI,3-NEWP,15-9.tif|Redwood Library and Athenaeum, Jane Stuart, mid-19th century\n</gallery>\n\n===Munro-Lenox type===\n* [[Minneapolis Institute of Art]], Minneapolis, Minnesota, by Thomas Sully, {{circa|1820}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Portrait of George Washington |url=https://collections.artsmia.org/art/486/portrait-of-george-washington-thomas-sully |publisher=[[Minneapolis Institute of Art]]|quote=Sully made many copies of Stuart's portraits of President Washington for government buildings and historical societies because Stuart could not meet the astonishing demand for them.}}</ref>\n* [[U.S. House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives Chamber]], U.S. Capitol,  by [[John Vanderlyn]], 1834<ref>{{cite web|title=Art and Artifacts|url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/Capitol/1951-Present/Art-and-Artifacts/|website=History, Art, and Archives|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], United Kingdom (on loan to [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]), unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), undated<ref>Lionel Cust, \"Stuart's Portrait of Washington,\" ''The Anglo-Saxon Review'', vol. 1, no. 1 (June 1899), (London and New York, John Lane), p. 85.[https://books.google.com/books?id=Bq1XAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Teapot+portrait+Washington&source=bl&ots=Ms3O4Vloi2&sig=9hyiRhh6NHhoPavxofp7_DJB1EA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXssDs-u7aAhUGhuAKHa-gC3IQ6AEIVjAL#v=onepage&q=Teapot%20portrait%20Washington&f=false]</ref>\n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, D.C. (on long-term loan), unknown artist, undated<ref>[http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_CT900004 George Washington (Munro-Lenox type)], from National Portrait Gallery.</ref>\n* [[Fall River Public Library]], [[Massachusetts]], by [[Robert Spear Dunning]], 1892<ref>{{cite web |title=Fall River Public Library Art Collection |url=https://fallriverlibrary.org/art.html |website=Fall River Library |accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Thomas Sully - Portrait of George Washington (1732\u20131799) - 32.12 - Minneapolis Institute of Arts.jpg|Minneapolis Institute of Art, Thomas Sully, c.1820\nFile:Portrait of George Washington 1834 by John Vanderlyn U.S. House of Reps.jpg|U.S. House of Representatives, John Vanderlyn, 1834\nFile:George Washington by Gilbert Stuart.jpg|Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, unknown artist, undated\nFile:George Washington after Gilbert Stuart by Robert Spear Dunning, Fall River Public Library.jpg|Fall River Public Library, Robert Spear Dunning, 1892\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\"The Portrait.\" ''George Washington: A National Treasure''. National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.georgewashington.si.edu/portrait/index.html georgewashington.si.edu]\n*Kellogg, Stuart. \"By George!\" [https://web.archive.org/web/20050409053403/http://www.vvdailypress.com/2001-2003/103743360089528.html Victor Valley Daily Press (CA)]. November 16, 2002.\n*Google Art Project: [http://www.googleartproject.com/collection/the-white-house/artwork/george-washington-gilbert-stuart/6494278/ White House copy], [http://www.googleartproject.com/collection/brooklyn-museum/artwork/george-washington-gilbert-stuart/6966745/ Brooklyn Museum copy]\n*[[Carrie Rebora Barratt]] and Ellen G. Miles, ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/74976 Gilbert Stuart, (2004),]'' a full text exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art \n*[http://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1700s/Artist-Gilbert-Stuart-s-portraits-of-George-Washington/ \"Artist Gilbert Stuart\u2019s Portraits of George Washington,\"] from History, Art & Archives, U.S. House of Representatives\n{{commons category|Lansdowne portrait of George Washington}}\n\n{{Gilbert Stuart|state=expanded}} \n{{George Washington}}\n\n[[Category:1796 paintings]]\n[[Category:George Washington in art]]\n[[Category:Paintings in the National Portrait Gallery (United States)]]\n[[Category:Paintings in the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Smithsonian American Art Museum]]\n[[Category:Paintings in the United States Capitol]]\n[[Category:Art in the White House]]\n[[Category:Portraits of politicians]]\n[[Category:Portraits of men]]\n[[Category:Books in art]]\n[[Category:18th-century portraits]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file=Gilbert Stuart, George Washington (Lansdowne portrait, 1796).jpg\n| title=''George Washington''<br>(''Lansdowne portrait of George Washington'')\n| artist=Gilbert Stuart\n| caption= \n| year=1796\n| medium=Oil on canvas\n| height_metric=247.6\n| width_metric=158.7\n| height_imperial=97.5\n| width_imperial=62.5\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| museum=[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, D.C.\n| italic title=no\n}}\nThe '''Lansdowne portrait''' is an [[cultural icon|icon]]ic life-size portrait of [[George Washington]] painted by [[Gilbert Stuart]] in 1796. It depicts the 64-year-old [[President of the United States]] during his final year in office. The portrait was a gift to former [[British Prime Minister]] [[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne|William Petty, 1st Marquess of Lansdowne]], and spent more than 170 years in England.\n\nStuart painted three copies of the Lansdowne, and five portraits that were closely related to it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|175}} The most famous of the copies is in the [[East Room]] of the [[White House]]. Numerous other artists have also painted copies.\n\nTo preclude the original portrait's possible sale at auction, the [[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]] in Washington, D.C. purchased it in 2001 for $20,000,000.<ref name=\"Kilian\">Michael Kilian, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-03-14-0103140255-story.html \"Timely Donation Saves Portrait of Washington from the Auction Block,\"] ''The Chicago Tribune'', March 14, 2001.</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Lansdowne portrait likely (and fancifully) depicts President Washington's December 7, 1795 annual address to the [[4th United States Congress|Fourth U.S. Congress]].<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} The highly-unpopular [[Jay Treaty]], settling claims between the United States and Great Britain left over from the Revolutionary War, had been presented for approval to the U.S. Senate earlier in the year. The Senate held a special session to debate the treaty in June, at which opposition to it had been fierce. Only two-thirds of the 30 senators (the minimum required under the U.S. Constitution) approved the treaty in mid-August, and Washington, who strongly supported the treaty, signed it in late August.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} In his annual address to Congress, on the opening day of its next session, President Washington acknowledged the struggle over the treaty and called for unity.<ref>[http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/index.php?pid=29437 George Washington - Seventh Annual Address to Congress], from The American Presidency Project.</ref> The portrait's paper, pen and inkwell may allude to his signing of the treaty.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}} There was lingering resentment in the House of Representatives, which expressed its displeasure by declining to appropriate funding for the treaty's implementation until April 1796.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\">Ellen G. Miles, \"\"Gilbert Stuart's 'Lansdowne' Portrait of George Washington: From Private Diplomatic Gift to State Portrait,\" lecture given at the National Portrait Gallery, September 25, 2014.[https://vimeo.com/133491164]</ref>\n\nIn England, the Lansdowne portrait was celebrated as Washington's endorsement of the Jay Treaty:\n\n<blockquote>The portrait presented by the President {{sic}} to the Marquis of Lansdowne is one of the finest pictures we have seen since the death of Reynolds. The dress he wears is plain black velvet; he has his sword on, upon the hilt of which one hand rests while the other is extended, as the figure is standing and addressing the Hall of Assembly. The point of time is that when he recommended inviolable union between America and Great Britain.<ref>''The Oracle and Public Advertiser'' (London), May 15, 1797.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWashington's December 7, 1795 address was the last that he delivered to Congress ''in person''. The following year the President published his [[George Washington's Farewell Address|Farewell Address]] in the newspapers, rather than delivering it to Congress.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|172}}\n\n==Stuart==\nStuart and his family were [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalists]], and moved from Rhode Island to Canada early in the [[American Revolution|Revolutionary War]].<ref name=\"NGA 2010\">[http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2005/stuart/philadelphia.shtm National Gallery of Art] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410110519/http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/2005/stuart/philadelphia.shtm |date=April 10, 2010 }}. ''Gilbert Stuart''. Philadelphia (1794\u20131803). Accessed: October 15, 2019.</ref> Stuart himself lived and painted in [[London]] from 1775 to 1787, and in [[Dublin]] from 1787 to 1793.<ref name=\"NGA 2010\"/> Following almost eighteen years abroad, the artist returned to the United States in early 1793.<ref name=\"NGA 2010\"/>\n\n[[William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne|Lord Lansdowne]] &ndash; who as [[British Prime Minister]] had secured a peaceful end to the War &ndash; commissioned Stuart to paint a portrait of George Washington.<ref>[https://history.blog.gov.uk/2015/08/26/william-petty-2nd-earl-of-shelburne-whig-1782-1783/ William Petty, 2nd Earl of Shelburne (Whig, 1782-1783)], from The National Archives (UK.gov).</ref> Lansdowne may have placed the order prior to the artist's 1793 return to the United States.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|80\u201381}} Stuart lived and worked in New York City for a year and a half before moving to Philadelphia in November 1794.<ref name=\"Zygmont\">\nBryan Zygmont, [https://www.khanacademy.org/humanities/art-americas/british-colonies/early-republic/a/gilbert-stuarts-lansdowne-portrait \"Gilbert Stuart's Lansdowne Portrait,\"] from Khan Academy.</ref> He informed his uncle in Philadelphia of his upcoming arrival: \"The object of my journey is only to secure a picture of the President, & finish yours.\"<ref>Stuart to Joseph Anthony, 2 November 1794, Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston. Quoted in Miles, pp. 129-30.</ref>\n\n[[Philadelphia]] served as the temporary national capital from 1790 to 1800 &ndash; while Washington, D.C. was under construction. Stuart was introduced to the President at one of Mrs. Washington's [[President's House (Philadelphia)|Friday evening \"drawingrooms,\"]] in December 1794.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|133}} But it was not until the following fall that Washington granted him a sitting. Meanwhile, Stuart gathered orders for portraits&mdash;among his papers is a document titled: \"A list of gentlemen who are to have copies of the portrait of the President of the United States.\" and dated: \"Philadelphia. April 20th, 1795.\"<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|87\u201388}} Lord Lansdowne's name was third on the list of thirty-two subscribers.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|87}}{{efn|In a September 25, 2014 lecture, Ellen G. Miles, Curator Emerita of the National Portrait Gallery, noted that others on Stuart's list of subscribers received copies of Washington head-and-bust portraits, but Lord Lansdowne received an original full-length portrait. She theorized that Lansdowne had ordered a standard portrait, but it was upgraded at Senator Bingham's suggestion (and expense) to an original and full-length portrait, a much more impressive gift.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/>}}\n\nAccording to [[Rembrandt Peale]], President Washington granted a single joint sitting to Stuart and him \"in the Autumn of 1795.\"<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88}} Stuart was not wholly satisfied with the resulting head-and-bust \"Vaughan-style\" portrait, but still painted between twelve and sixteen copies of it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|135}} He later claimed to have destroyed his original.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88}} \n\nWhile visiting London a decade earlier, [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[William Bingham]] of [[Pennsylvania]] and his wife, Anne Willing Bingham, had sat for a family portrait by Stuart (abandoned).<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|198}} The artist seems to have approached Mrs. Bingham for assistance in getting the President to grant him another sitting:<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|91}}\n\n{{quote|\n::Mr. Stuart, Chestnut Street.\n\n:::Sir\n\n:::&mdash; I am under promise to Mrs. Bingham to set for you to-morrow at nine o'clock, and wishing to know if it be convenient to you that should do so, whether it shall be at your own house (as she talked of the State House) I send this note to you to ask information.\n\n::::::::::::::::I am Sir, Your \n\n::::::::::::::::obedient Serv<sup>t</sup>\n\n:::::::::::::::::::Ge<sup>o</sup>. \n\n:::::::::::::::::::WASHINGTON.\n\n::Monday Evening, 11th Ap<sup>r</sup> 1796.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|88\u201389}}}}\n\nAccording to Rembrandt Peale, this was the only sitting that Washington granted for the Lansdowne portrait.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\">Ellen Gross Miles, \"George Washington (The Lansdowne Portrait),\" in ''Gilbert Stuart'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2004), pp. 166-90.</ref>{{rp|168}} It took place at Stuart's studio (and lodgings) in the William Moore Smith house, at the southeast corner of 5th & Chestnut Streets.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|168}} With severely limited time, Stuart was forced to concentrate on the President's head and face.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|168}} There are multiple claims as to who posed for the body of the figure, including his landlord, Smith.{{efn|In [[George Washington Parke Custis|\"Wash\" Custis]]'s description of Washington's annual address to Congress (either 1794 or 1795, based on Thomas Jefferson's presence), he wrote: \"Washington was dressed precisely as Stuart has painted him in Lord Lansdowne's full-length portrait&mdash;\" and then proceeded to give a detailed description. On the portrait: \"The defect in the full-length is in the limbs. For the figure, a man named Smith, with whom Stuart boarded, stood&mdash;a smaller man than Washington; and the hands were painted from a wax cast of Stuart's own hand, which was much smaller than Washington's.\" On the mouth: \"Washington, at the time Stuart painted his portrait, had a set of sea-horse ivory teeth. These, just made, were too large and clumsy, and gave that peculiar appearance of the mouth seen in Stuart's picture.\"<ref>G. W. Parke Custis, ''Recollections and Private Memoirs of Washington'' (New York: Derby & Jackson, 1860), pp. 491, 520-23.</ref>}}\n\nThe portrait was begun by Stuart in his Philadelphia studio and completed in his [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] studio, the second floor of a stable some 8 miles north of the city.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|130\u201331}} The artist moved to Germantown in Summer 1796 to avoid distractions.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|165\u201366}} The Binghams had enjoyed Lord Lansdowne's hospitality in London, and persuaded Stuart to allow them to pay for the portrait.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|166, 168}} Stuart completed the Lansdowne portrait by the fall of 1796, and Senator Bingham paid his fee of $1,000.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|170}} Bingham had an ornate frame made for the portrait, and arranged for it to be shipped to England in late November. Lord Lansdowne had received the portrait by March 5, 1797, when he mentioned it in a letter.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|92}} Lansdowne's letter of thanks to Mrs. Bingham survives, but is undated:\n\n<blockquote>A very fine portrait of the greatest man living in a magnificent frame found its way into my hall, with no one thing left for me to do regarding it, except to thank the amiable donor of it. It is universally approv'd and admir'd, and I see with satisfaction, that there is no one who does not turn away from every thing else, to pay their homage to General Washington. Among many circumstances which contribute to enhance the value of it, I shall always consider the quarter from whence it comes as most flattering, & I look forward with the greatest pleasure to the time of shewing you and Mr. Bingham where I have plac'd it.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|170}}</blockquote>\n\n===Copies===\nStuart's first copy of the portrait was for the Binghams (now at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]]), and would have been completed before the original left his studio in late 1796.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/> The President and First Lady visited Germantown on January 7, 1797: \"Road [rode] to German Town with Mrs. Washington to see Mr. Stuarts paintings.\"<ref>Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds., ''The Diaries of George Washington, Volume 6'' (Charlottesville: University of Virginia Press, 1976&ndash;79), p. 229.</ref> The Bingham copy was still in the studio on July 27, 1797, where Robert Gilmor Jr. viewed it.<ref name=\"Gilmor\">Robert Gilmor Jr., ''Memorandums Made in a Tour to the Eastern States in the Year 1797'' (Boston: Trustees of the Boston Public Library, 1892), p. 6.</ref> The William Kerin Constable copy (now at the [[Brooklyn Museum]]) was completed that same month.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}} The Gardiner Baker copy (now at the White House) is presumed to have been the copy commissioned by [[Charles Cotesworth Pinckney]] in September 1796, likely as a diplomatic gift to France.{{efn|Art historian Ellen G. Miles has a theory as to why Charles Cotesworth Pinckney commissioned and paid for a copy of the Lansdowne portrait, but never retrieved it from Gilbert Stuart's studio.<br>[[James Monroe]] was Minister to France in 1795, when the Jay Treaty was signed. France was then at war with Great Britain, and despite his best efforts, Monroe could not convince the French government that this was a benign treaty and would not affect Franco-American relations. President Washington recalled Monroe, and nominated Pinckney as his successor. Pinckney was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in September 1796, and arrived in Paris in November.<br>The [[French Directory]] refused to accept Pinckney's credentials, and negotiations between the countries broke down when French officials demanded a substantial bribe to do so, in what became known as the [[XYZ Affair]].<br>Miles's theory is that Pinckney's copy of the Lansdowne portrait was intended as a diplomatic gift from the U.S. to France. Pinckney's deliberate humiliation and the suspension of diplomatic relations between the countries (for nearly 5 years) caused those plans (and the portrait) to be abandoned.<br>Supporting evidence for the diplomatic gift theory is that Pinckney later sought reimbursement from Secretary of State Timothy Pickering for the $500 that he had paid to Stuart for the portrait.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/>}} Pinckney paid for but never retrieved his copy of the portrait from Stuart's studio, and the artist seems to have resold it to Baker by December 1797.<ref name=\"Stretch\">Bonnie Barrett Stretch, \"The White House Washington, If Stuart Didn't Paint It, Who Did?\" ''ArtNews'', October 1, 2004.[http://www.artnews.com/2004/10/01/the-white-house-washington/]</ref>\n\n==Provenance==\n<blockquote>After the death of Lord Lansdowne, his pictures were sold by auction. The ''Washington'' was purchased by Samuel Williams, an English {{sic}} merchant, for $2,000. Williams subsequently became insolvent, and his creditors disposed of the ''Washington'' by a lottery. Forty tickets were sold, at fifty guineas each. The picture fell to Mr. J. Delaware Lewis, a nephew of Mr. William D. Lewis, of Philadelphia. But few Americans had ever seen the picture, and Mr. William D. Lewis, who was Chairman of the Committee on Art, obtained the loan of it from his nephew for the [[1876 Centennial Exposition|Centennial Exhibition]]. It was sent out with the loan collection from England, unpacked at [[Memorial Hall (Philadelphia)|Memorial Hall]], and hung up in the British section before its arrival was known to the Fine Arts Committee. An effort was subsequently made to have it transferred to the American section, but it was unsuccessful. At the close of the Exhibition, it was returned to its owner in England.<ref name=\"Mason\">George Champlin Mason, ''The Life and Works of Gilbert Stuart'' (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1894).</ref>{{rp|13}}</blockquote>\n\n===Chronology===\n*1796 &ndash; Painted by Gilbert Stuart.\n*1797 &ndash; Presented by Senator William Bingham and his wife Anne Willing Bingham as a gift to William Petty, the first Marquis of Lansdowne (died 1805). \n*1806 &ndash; Purchased in March, at the sale of the Marquis's estate by Samuel Williams, an American merchant living in England.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1827 &ndash; Purchased through lottery by John Delaware Lewis (1774&ndash;1841), an American merchant living in England.<ref name=\"Provenance\">{{cite web |title=George Washington (Lansdowne Portrait); see section ''Provenance''|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2001.13 |website=National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution |accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> \n*1841 &ndash; Inherited by [[John Delaware Lewis]] Jr. (1828&ndash;1884), son of the American and later a British Member of Parliament<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1876 &ndash; Exhibited at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia.\n*1884 &ndash; Inherited by Herman LeRoy Lewis.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1889 &ndash; Purchased by Archibald Philip Primrose, fifth Earl of Rosebery; by family descent to Lord Harry Dalmeny.<ref name=\"Provenance\"/>\n*1968 &ndash; Placed on long-term loan to the National Portrait Gallery.<ref name=\"NGA\">[http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2001.13 George Washington (Lansdowne Portrait)], from National Portrait Gallery.</ref> \n*2001 &ndash; Purchased by the National Portrait Gallery, with $20 million from [[The Donald W. Reynolds Foundation]].<ref name=\"Kilian\"/> The Foundation donated an additional $10 million to renovate the National Portrait Gallery and to fund a traveling exhibition of the portrait.<ref>[http://www.dwreynolds.org/Programs/Special/Special.htm Donald W. Reynolds Foundation, ''Special Projects'']</ref>\n\n==Description and Analysis==\n[[File:Lansdowne portrait table leg.png|140px|thumb|left|The table leg may have been inspired by a wooden [[ceremonial mace]] used by the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] (the U.S. House symbol was itself inspired by the Roman ''[[fasces]]''). The House mace was a bundle of tied reeds topped with a [[bald eagle]], an American symbol.]]\n[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington (detail of book labels) - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|Detail of the book bindings in the White House's copy of the Lansdowne portrait. \"UNITED STATES\" is spelled as \"UNITED SATES\" to distinguish the copy.]]\nThe painting is full of symbolism, drawn from American and [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] symbols of the [[Roman Republic]]. Stuart painted Washington from life, showing him standing up, dressed in a black [[velvet]] suit with an outstretched hand held up in an [[Eloquence|oratorical]] manner. Behind Washington is a row of two [[Doric column]]s, with another row to the left. Wrapped around and between the columns are red tasseled drapes.\n\nWashington's suit is plain and simple, and the [[sword]] he holds on his left side is a dress sword and not a battle sword (symbolizing a [[Democracy|democratic]] [[form of government]], rather than a [[monarchy]] or [[military dictatorship]]). In the sky, storm clouds appear on the left while a [[rainbow]] appears on the right, signifying the [[American Revolutionary War]] giving way to the peace and prosperity of the new [[United States]] after the 1783 [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]]. The medallion at the top of the chair shows the red, white, and blue colors of the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]].\n\nOn and under the tablecloth-draped table to the left are two [[book]]s: ''Federalist''&mdash;probably a reference to the ''[[Federalist Papers]]''&mdash;and ''Journal of Congress''&mdash;the ''[[Congressional Record]]''. Another five books are under the table: the three to the right are ''General Orders'', ''American Revolution'', and ''Constitutional Bylaws''&mdash;symbolizing Washington's leadership as [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[Continental Army]] and [[President of the Continental Congress|president]] of the [[Philadelphia Convention|Constitutional Convention]].\n\nThe [[pen]] and [[paper]] on the table signify the [[rule of law]]. The table's leg is shaped like a [[fasces]], an ancient Roman symbol of [[power (sociology)|power]] and [[authority]] (''[[imperium]]''). On the far left of the table is a [[silver]] [[inkwell]], emblazed with [[Coat of Arms of George Washington|George Washington's coat of arms]] (see [[Syng inkstand]]). A white [[quill]] rests upon silver [[dog]]s, ancient symbols of [[loyalty]]. Behind these on the table is a large black [[hat]].\n\nWashington's unusually clenched [[facial expression]] comes from his famous [[Dentures|false teeth]]. [[Jean-Antoine Houdon]]'s [[marble]] [[sculpture]] of Washington shows a more natural expression. Stuart wrote: \"When I painted him [Washington], he had just had a set of false teeth inserted, which accounts for the constrained expression so noticeable about the mouth and lower part of the face ... Houdon's [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] does not suffer from this defect.\"\n\n==Alternate versions==\n===Constable-Hamilton portrait===\nStuart painted a 1797 seated portrait of Washington, based on the Lansdowne. William Kerin Constable, who commissioned the Lansdowne copy now at the Brooklyn Museum, also commissioned the seated version.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|98}} Constable presented it to [[Alexander Hamilton]] in 1797.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>{{rp|98}} The portrait remained in the Hamilton family until 1896, when it was bequeathed to the [[Lenox Library (New York City)|Lenox Library]].<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/> The Lenox Library later merged with the [[New York Public Library]]. The portrait was auctioned at Sotheby's NY, 30 November 2005, lot 3, and sold for $8,136,000.<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2005/american-paintings-drawings-sculpture-including-property-from-the-new-york-public-library-astor-lenox-and-tilden-foundations-n08134/lot.3.html George Washington (Constable-Hamilton Portrait)], from Sotheby's NY.</ref> The Constable-Hamilton Portrait is now in the collection of the [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], in [[Bentonville, Arkansas]].<ref name=\"CBMAA\">[http://collection.crystalbridges.org/objects/193/george-washington-the-constablehamilton-portrait?ctx=cf2d7cdf-4879-41e8-9884-d94fb9947503&idx=2 George Washington - The Constable-Hamilton Portrait], from Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art.</ref>\n\n===Munro-Lenox portrait===\nStuart made several changes for the Munro-Lenox portrait ({{circa}}1800):<ref name=\"SIRIS\">[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=D52X1907708G8.5587&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!47905~!2&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Lenox&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington - The Munro-Lenox Portrait], from SIRIS.</ref> Washington's head is slightly turned, and his hand is on the table, rather than gesturing into the air. The President looks directly at the viewer, rather than off to the side, which makes it a more compelling image than the Lansdowne.<ref name=\"Miles\"/> The head appears to be based on Stuart's Athenaeum portrait (the image on the one-dollar bill).<ref name=\"Miles\"/> The wall behind the President is lowered, allowing for a more dramatic scene of the sun breaking through the storm clouds. After 135 years of ownership by the [[New York Public Library]], the Munro-Lenox portrait was deassessioned and offered for auction in 2005.<ref name=\"Sotheby's\">[http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/lot.5.html/2005/american-paintings-drawings-sculpture-including-property-from-the-new-york-public-library-astor-lenox-and-tilden-foundations-n08134 George Washington - The Munro-Lenox Portrait], from Sotheby's New York.</ref> It failed to sell at auction, and was sold in a private sale for an undisclosed amount.<ref>Carol Vogel, [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/05/arts/design/05voge.html \"A Pair of New Owners for an Old President,\"] ''The New York Times'', January 5, 2007.</ref>\n\nStuart painted three full-size copies of the Munro-Lenox Portrait, one for the Connecticut State House in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]]; and two for Rhode Island&mdash;one for the State House in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], and the other for [[Old Colony House]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]].<ref name=\"Miles\">Ellen Gross Miles, \"George Washington (The Munro-Lenox Portrait),\" in ''Gilbert Stuart'' (Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2004), pp. 186-90.</ref>\n\n==Painted by Gilbert Stuart==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\" | Type\n! width=\"18%\" | Collection\n! width=\"8%\" | Image\n! width=\"10%\" | Artist\n! width=\"9%\" | Completed\n! width=\"8%\" | Medium\n! width=\"10%\" | Dimensions\n! width=\"32%\" | Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Lansdowne type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Lansdowne portrait<ref name=\"NGA\"/><br>National Portrait Gallery,<br>Washington, D.C.\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart, George Washington (Lansdowne portrait, 1796).jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|Fall 1796\n|oil on canvas\n|247.6&nbsp;cm x 158.7&nbsp;cm<br>(97 1/2 x 62 1/2 in)\n|Begun April 12, 1796<br>Unsigned & undated\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]],<ref>[http://artandhistory.house.gov/highlights.aspx?action=view&intID=351 Office of the Clerk, U.S. House of Representatives, ''Artist Gilbert Stuart\u2019s portraits of George Washington''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915082823/http://artandhistory.house.gov/highlights.aspx?action=view&intID=351 |date=2012-09-15 }} Accessed: May 11, 2012.</ref><br>Philadelphia, Pennsylvania\n|[[File:Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts - Washington Foyer.jpg|100px]]<br><small>at far left</small>\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by November 1796\n|oil on canvas\n|243.8&nbsp;cm x 152.4&nbsp;cm<br>(96 in x 60 in)\n|Commissioned by Senator William Bingham.<br>First copy painted by Stuart.<br>Signed & dated: \"G. Stuart, 1796\"<ref>Helen W. Henderson, ''The Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts and Other Collections in Philadelphia'' (Boston: L. C. Page & Company, 1899), frontispiece, p. 81.[https://archive.org/stream/pennsylvaniaacad00hend_0#page/80/mode/2up]</ref> <br>Present in Stuart's [[Germantown, Philadelphia|Germantown]] studio, July 1797<ref name=\"Gilmor\"/><br>1811 bequest to PAFA<ref>[https://www.pafa.org/collection/george-washington-lansdowne-portrait George Washington (Bingham portrait)], from Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts.</ref>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Brooklyn Museum]],<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\" /><br>Brooklyn, [[New York City]]\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington - Google Art Project (6966745)FXD.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|July 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|244.5&nbsp;cm x 153&nbsp;cm<br>(96 1/4 in x 60 1/4 in)\n|Commissioned by William Kerin Constable.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15VY14267968R.5068&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!41116~!2&ri=3&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Lansdowne&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=3 George Washington (Constable portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><br>Unsigned & undated<br>Constable paid Stuart $500 for \"one [portrait] of the late President of the United States at full length.\" Constable's receipt from Stuart is signed and dated \"Philadelphia. 13 July 1797.\"<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}}<br>1945 museum purchase<ref>[https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/934 George Washington, Gilbert Stuart], from Brooklyn Museum.</ref>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[White House]], [[East Room]],<br>Washington, D.C.\n|[[File:Gilbert Stuart - George Washington - Google Art Project.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart (and<br>William Winstanley?){{efn|The comparably poor quality of the Lansdowne copy at the White House has led to questions and conspiracy theories about its authorship.<ref name=\"Stretch\"/><br>After Stuart toured the White House with Dr. [[William Thornton]] in 1802, [[Anna Thornton|Thornton's wife]] wrote to Dolley Madison: \"He [Stuart] denies most pointedly having painted the picture in the President's house, and says he told Genl: Lee that he did not paint it&mdash;but that he bargained for it.\"<ref>Anna Maria Thornton to Dolley Madison, August 24, 1802, in David B. Mattern and Holly C. Shulman, eds. ''The Selected Letters of Dolley Payne Madison'' (Charlottesville: University of Virginia Press, 2003, pp. 50-51.</ref><br>Artist William Dunlap wrote (in 1834) that William Winstanley was hired to pack the Washington portrait bought for the White House in July 1800, and substituted his own copy for Stuart's prior to its being shipped from New York City to Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Dunlap\"/> Dunlap also reported that Winstanley had approached Stuart about putting finishing touches on his pirated Lansdowne copies, proposing that they could share the proceeds, but Stuart angrily rejected the idea.<ref name=\"Dunlap\"/><br>Regarding Stuart's denial of the White House Lansdowne, Ellen G. Miles writes: \"The comment does suggest that Stuart did not paint the entire portrait.\" ''Gilbert Stuart'' (2004), p. 181, n. 23.}}\n|by December 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|241.3&nbsp;cm x 151.9&nbsp;cm<br>(95 in x 59 3/4 in)\n|Probably commissioned by Charles Cotesworth Pinckney, September 1796, as a diplomatic gift to France.<ref name=\"Miles lecture\"/><br>Unsigned & undated<br>Purchased from Stuart by Gardiner Baker for $500, by December 1797.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181}}<br>Exhibited at Tammany Society Museum, New York City, February 1798.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181}}<br>Purchased for the White House for $800, July 1800.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|88}}<br>Rescued by First Lady [[Dolley Madison]] prior to the August 24, 1814 [[Burning of Washington#White House|burning of the White House]] by the British.<ref>{{cite web|title=The East Room|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/white-house-tour/the-east-room|website=The White House Historical Association|publisher=The White House Historical Association|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Constable-Hamilton type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Constable-Hamilton Portrait<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/><br>Ex collection: Lenox Library<br>Ex collection:New York Public Library<br>[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]],<br>Bentonville, Arkansas\n|[[File:Stuart-george-washington-constable-1797.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|July 1797\n|oil on canvas\n|127&nbsp;cm x 101.6&nbsp;cm<br>(50 in x 40 in)\n|Commissioned by William Kerin Constable, as a gift to Alexander Hamilton.<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/><br>Constable paid $250 for the \"half-length\" portrait. His receipt from Stuart is signed and dated \"Philadelphia. 13 July 1797.\"<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|178}}<br>1896 bequest to the Lenox Library (later merged with New York Public Library)<ref name=\"CBMAA\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:#C80815\" | '''Munro-Lenox type'''\n|-\n|Original\n|Munro-Lenox Portrait<ref name=\"SIRIS\"/><br>Ex collection: Lenox Library<br>Ex collection: New York Public Library<br>Private collection\n|[[File:Munro-Lenox Portrait from NYPL.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|{{circa}}1800\n|oil on canvas\n|241.3&nbsp;cm x 162.6&nbsp;cm<br>(95 in x 64 in)\n|Commissioned by Peter Jay Munro<br>Signed \"G. St.\" (on table leg), undated<br>Donated to the Lenox Library, 1870.<br>Auctioned at Sotheby's NY, 30 November 2005, Lot 5.<ref name=\"Sotheby's\"/>\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Old State House (Connecticut)|Old State House]],<br>Connecticut State Library Museum,<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=Q5251706WV553.5346&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!35638~!9&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Hartford&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart,+Gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Hartford portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><br>[[Hartford, Connecticut]]\n|\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|April 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|240.4&nbsp;cm x 146.1&nbsp;cm<br>(94 5/8 in x 57 1/2 in)\n|Commissioned by the [[Connecticut General Assembly]], May 1800.<ref name=\"Johnston\">Elizabeth Bryant Johnston, ''Original Portraits of Washington'' (Boston: James R. Osgood & Company, 1882).</ref>{{rp|90}}<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gosselin|first1=Kenneth|title=Old State House To Reopen Monday|url=http://www.courant.com/real-estate/property-line/hc-old-state-house-reopens-20161122-story.html|website=Hartford Courant|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tourist in My Own State: Connecticut's Old State House|url=http://www.thefrontdoorproject.com/2015/09/historic-doors/tourist-in-my-own-state-connecticuts-old-state-house/|website=The Front Door Project|accessdate=25 February 2018|date=21 September 2015}}</ref><br>Connecticut paid $600 for the portrait. The receipt, signed by Stuart and dated 4 April 1801, is in the Connecticut State Archives.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|189\u201390}}\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Rhode Island State House]],<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=15DN1Q0244473.5338&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!60262~!16&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Rhode+Island&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=stuart,+gilbert&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Providence portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Rhode Island State House: A Guided Tour|url=http://sos.ri.gov/assets/downloads/documents/self-guided-state-house-tour-brochure.pdf|website=State of Rhode Island|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><br>State Reception Room, <br>[[Providence, Rhode Island]].\n|[[File:State_Reception_Room,_Rhode_Island_State_House.jpg|100px]]\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by October 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|<br>(96 in x 60 in)\n|Rhode Island had statehouses in both Providence and Newport (until 1901). The [[Rhode Island General Assembly]] commissioned 2 copies of the Munro-Lenox portrait in 1800, one for each statehouse.<ref name=\"Johnston\"/>{{rp|89}}<br>The elaborate wooden frame was carved and gilded by Martin Jugiez, a Philadelphia carver.<ref name=\"Miles\"/><br>Both portraits (and their ornate frames) were transported by ship from Philadelphia, and arrived at Newport in October 1801.{{efn|\"The commission was at once given to Gilbert Stuart, who took pride and pleasure in painting the portraits; for which work he received $1,200. The pictures were painted in Philadelphia, where the frames were also procured at a cost of $200 each. When finished, the portraits and frames were placed in the care of Joseph Anthony & Co., of Philadelphia, by whom they were shipped to Rhode Island on board of Gibbs & Channing's sloop ''Eagle''. The pictures were received here in October 1801.\"<ref>George Champlin Mason, ''Reminiscences of Newport'' (Newport, RI: Charles E. Hammett, Jr., 1884), pp. 290-91.</ref>}}\n|-\n|Copy\n|[[Old Colony House]] (formerly<br>Rhode Island State House, Newport),<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=152K1Q9C92979.5706&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!60274~!5&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=colony+house&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=Stuart&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Newport portrait)], from SIRIS.</ref><ref>James L. Yarnell, \"The Full-Length Portrait of George Washington in the Newport Colony House,\" ''Newport History: Journal of the Newport Historical Society'', nos. 72-73 (Fall 2003&ndash;Spring 2004), pp. 150-59.</ref><br>[[Newport, Rhode Island]]\n|\n|Gilbert Stuart\n|by October 1801\n|oil on canvas\n|\n|Old Colony House served as a Rhode Island State House until 1901.<ref>[http://newporthistory.org/properties/colony-house/ Colony House], from Newport Historical Society.</ref><br>The elaborate wooden frame was carved and gilded by Martin Jugiez, a Philadelphia carver.<ref name=\"Miles\"/><br>Arrived by ship at Newport, October 1801.<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|188}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Copies painted by other artists==\nThe Lansdowne and Munro-Lenox portraits were copied many times, and reproduced in widely circulated prints.<ref name=\"BrooklynMuseum\">{{cite web|title=American Art: Luce Center for American Art, 5th Floor|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/american_art|website=Brooklyn Museum|accessdate=25 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120101614/https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/american_art/|archivedate=29 June 2016}}</ref> William Winstanley (1775&ndash;1806), a British painter who had sold landscapes to President Washington,<ref>George Washington to the Commissioners for the District of Columbia, 5 September 1793, note 1, from National Archives.[https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/05-14-02-0019]</ref> reportedly painted six full-size copies of the Lansdowne.<ref name=\"Dunlap\">William Dunlap, ''History of the Rise and Progress of the Arts of Design in the United States'' vol. 1 (New York: George C. Scott and Co., 1834), pp. 200-02.</ref> During the 19th century, [[Jane Stuart]] (the artist's daughter) painted multiple copies of the Lansdowne in full and reduced sizes. [[Alonzo Chappel]] included elements of the Lansdowne in his {{circa}}1860 seated portrait of Washington ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]).<ref>[https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/10436?sortBy=Relevance&amp;ft=Chappel%2c+Alonzo&amp;offset=0&amp;rpp=20&amp;pos=1 George Washington - Design for an Engraving, (c. 1860) by Alonzo Chappel], from Metropolitan Museum of Art.</ref>\n\n===Lansdowne type===\n* [[Catholic University]], Washington, D.C., unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181\u201382}}\n* [[Washington and Lee University]], Lexington, Virginia, unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|182}}\n* Private collection (deassessioned from the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]), unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), 1798 or later<ref name=\"Lansdowne\"/>{{rp|181\u201382}}\n* [[New York State Capitol]], Albany, New York, by [[Ezra Ames]], 1813<ref>{{cite book|author1=John Caldwell, Oswaldo Rodriguez Roque, Dale T. Johnson|title=American Paintings in The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Vol. 1|date=1994|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|page=239|accessdate=31 March 2018|quote=clearly based on the Stuart Lansdowne portrait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYdWBwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA240&ots=qgszBj4zHp&dq=landsdowne%20portrait%20in%20albany%20new%20york%20capitol&pg=PA240#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n* Rayburn Room, [[U.S. Capitol]], unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), by 1816<ref>{{cite web|title=Art and Artifacts George Washington's Journey to the Rayburn Room|url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/Capitol/Rayburn-Reception-Room/Art-and-Artifacts/|website=History, Art, & Archives|publisher=US House of Representatives|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n**Inscription: \"Presented to the Legation of the United States at Madrid by [[Richard Worsam Meade I|Richard W. Meade]] of Philadelphia, December 11th, 1818.\"\n**Relocated from the U.S. Embassy in Madrid to the U.S. Capitol, 1951.\n* [[North Carolina State House]], Raleigh, North Carolina, by [[Thomas Sully]], commissioned 1816, installed 1818. Now in the House of Representatives Chamber, [[North Carolina State Capitol]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Exhibit and Reinstallation of Washington Portrait This April |url=https://www.ncdcr.gov/state-capitol-debuts-george-washington-exhibit-and-reinstallation-washington-portrait-april |publisher=[[North Carolina Department of Natural and Cultural Resources]] |date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Maryland Historical Society]], Baltimore, Maryland, unknown artist, {{circa}}1830s<ref>{{cite web|title=George Washington|url=https://www.mdhs.org/digitalimage/george-washington|website=Maryland Historical Society|publisher=Maryland Historical Society|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Providence Athenaeum]], Providence, Rhode Island, unknown Italian artist, {{circa}}1830s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Art Collection: Painting|url=https://providenceathenaeum.org/collections/art-collection/painting/|website=The Providence Athenaeum|accessdate=25 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822015129/https://providenceathenaeum.org/collections/art-collection/painting/|archivedate=22 August 2016|quote=George Washington, circa 1830s. Anonymous, after Gilbert Stuart (1755-1828). Oil on canvas. Gift of The Honorable Samuel Larned, 1838.}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Art Gallery]], Washington, D.C., by Jane Stuart, 1854.<ref>''A Catalogue of the Collection of American Paintings in The Corcoran Gallery of Art, Volume 1'' (The Corcoran Gallery of Art, 1966), p. 81.</ref>\n*[[The Greenbrier]], White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia, by Jane Stuart, mid-19th century.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=S52545711L85V.2091&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!149308~!14&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Greenbriar&index=.OW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1 George Washington (Greenbrier)], from SIRIS.</ref>\n*Kuhl-Harrison reduced-size portrait, (36 1/4 in x 24 in), unlocated, Gilbert Stuart and Jane Stuart, 19th century.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/europeanamerican00amer_0#page/n47/mode/2up George Washington: Lansdowne Type (The Kuhl-Harrison Portrait)], from Anderson Galleries Inc., New York, 1936.</ref>\n*Reduced-size portrait, [[Redwood Library and Athenaeum]], Newport, Rhode Island, Jane Stuart, mid-19th century.<ref>[https://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1525A46322NE1.4870&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!59811~!85&ri=23&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Stuart,+Jane&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=23 George Washington (Redwood Library)], from SIRIS.</ref>\n*[[Birmingham Museum of Art]], Birmingham, Alabama, by [[Theo Ramos|Theodore Ramos]] (1928-2018), 1965.<ref>[https://artsbma.org/collection/copy-of-lansdowne-portrait-of-george-washington-by-gilbert-stuart/ Copy of Lansdowne Portrait], from Birmingham Museum of Art.</ref> On loan to [[Alabama National Cemetery#American Village|American Village]], Montevallo, Alabama.\n<gallery>\nFile:Lansdowne portrait copy in New York State Capitol.jpg|New York State Capitol, Ezra Ames, 1813\nFile:Lansdowne copy Rayburn Room U.S. House of Representatives.jpg|Rayburn Room, U.S. Capitol, unknown artist, by 1816\nFile:House of Representatives Chamber - North Carolina State Capitol - DSC05940.JPG|North Carolina State Capitol, Thomas Sully, 1818\nFile:Lansdowne portrait of George Washington copy at Providence Athenaeum.jpg|Providence Athenaeum, unknown artist, 1830s\nFile:Historic American Buildings Survey, Cervin Robinson, Photographer, July 15, 1970 VIEW OF INTERIOR FROM READING (CENTER) ROOM TO DOOR WEST. - Redwood Library, 50 Bellevue Avenue, HABS RI,3-NEWP,15-9.tif|Redwood Library and Athenaeum, Jane Stuart, mid-19th century\n</gallery>\n\n===Munro-Lenox type===\n* [[Minneapolis Institute of Art]], Minneapolis, Minnesota, by Thomas Sully, {{circa|1820}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Portrait of George Washington |url=https://collections.artsmia.org/art/486/portrait-of-george-washington-thomas-sully |publisher=[[Minneapolis Institute of Art]]|quote=Sully made many copies of Stuart's portraits of President Washington for government buildings and historical societies because Stuart could not meet the astonishing demand for them.}}</ref>\n* [[U.S. House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives Chamber]], U.S. Capitol,  by [[John Vanderlyn]], 1834<ref>{{cite web|title=Art and Artifacts|url=http://history.house.gov/Exhibitions-and-Publications/Capitol/1951-Present/Art-and-Artifacts/|website=History, Art, and Archives|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], United Kingdom (on loan to [[Montreal Museum of Fine Arts]]), unknown artist (possibly William Winstanley), undated<ref>Lionel Cust, \"Stuart's Portrait of Washington,\" ''The Anglo-Saxon Review'', vol. 1, no. 1 (June 1899), (London and New York, John Lane), p. 85.[https://books.google.com/books?id=Bq1XAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Teapot+portrait+Washington&source=bl&ots=Ms3O4Vloi2&sig=9hyiRhh6NHhoPavxofp7_DJB1EA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXssDs-u7aAhUGhuAKHa-gC3IQ6AEIVjAL#v=onepage&q=Teapot%20portrait%20Washington&f=false]</ref>\n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, D.C. (on long-term loan), unknown artist, undated<ref>[http://npg.si.edu/object/npg_CT900004 George Washington (Munro-Lenox type)], from National Portrait Gallery.</ref>\n* [[Fall River Public Library]], [[Massachusetts]], by [[Robert Spear Dunning]], 1892<ref>{{cite web |title=Fall River Public Library Art Collection |url=https://fallriverlibrary.org/art.html |website=Fall River Library |accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Thomas Sully - Portrait of George Washington (1732\u20131799) - 32.12 - Minneapolis Institute of Arts.jpg|Minneapolis Institute of Art, Thomas Sully, c.1820\nFile:Portrait of George Washington 1834 by John Vanderlyn U.S. House of Reps.jpg|U.S. House of Representatives, John Vanderlyn, 1834\nFile:George Washington by Gilbert Stuart.jpg|Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, unknown artist, undated\nFile:George Washington after Gilbert Stuart by Robert Spear Dunning, Fall River Public Library.jpg|Fall River Public Library, Robert Spear Dunning, 1892\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*\"The Portrait.\" ''George Washington: A National Treasure''. National Portrait Gallery, Smithsonian Institution. [http://www.georgewashington.si.edu/portrait/index.html georgewashington.si.edu]\n*Kellogg, Stuart. \"By George!\" [https://web.archive.org/web/20050409053403/http://www.vvdailypress.com/2001-2003/103743360089528.html Victor Valley Daily Press (CA)]. November 16, 2002.\n*Google Art Project: [http://www.googleartproject.com/collection/the-white-house/artwork/george-washington-gilbert-stuart/6494278/ White House copy], [http://www.googleartproject.com/collection/brooklyn-museum/artwork/george-washington-gilbert-stuart/6966745/ Brooklyn Museum copy]\n*[[Carrie Rebora Barratt]] and Ellen G. Miles, ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/74976 Gilbert Stuart, (2004),]'' a full text exhibition catalog from The Metropolitan Museum of Art \n*[http://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1700s/Artist-Gilbert-Stuart-s-portraits-of-George-Washington/ \"Artist Gilbert Stuart\u2019s Portraits of George Washington,\"] from History, A